<div id="section_2">
	<div id="sub_section_2" class="section">
		<h3>NARRATIVE FORM - CONVENTION AND EXPECTATION</h3>
		<p id="graphic_3_in">
			When a filmmaker makes a film, she is typically not simply interested in telling a story. Usually, she's interested in created an emotional experience, something that involves taking the viewer through a progression of a range of feelings. The filmmaker is highly attuned to the viewer's emotional state at all times and intentionally employs specific strategies to move the viewer from one emotional state to another. 
		</p>
		<p id="graphic_4_in">
			In order to create this progression, the filmmaker makes use of something called "narrative form." When we talk about narrative form, we're talking about an established system that creates <em>expectations</em>: a pattern. Those expectations are created when a pattern is repeated over a long period of time: we see a certain combination of shots, and we develop expectations about what's coming next. 
		</p>
		<p>
			We can call these patterns <em>conventions</em>. Conventions can be useful tools that filmmakers employ to complex effect, or they can be cliched, cheap shorthand, intended to trigger stereotypical emotional reactions by rote.	
		</p>
		<p id="expectations">
			The expectations created by conventions are also tools that a filmmaker can use. If the filmmaker knows the viewer has certain expectations, she can choose to respond to those expectations in different ways. She can choose to <strong>fulfill</strong> those expectations, giving the viewers what they think they're going to get. Or she can instead choose to <strong>thwart</strong> expectations, denying the viewers the resolution of those expectations. Additionally, she can choose to <strong>delay</strong> expectations, forcing viewers to wait in anticipation. 	
		</p>
		<p>
			Each of these strategies can result in a variety of different effects on the viewer. When expectations are <em>fulfilled</em>, a viewer is likely to experience one of a range of emotions, from satisfaction to relief to perhaps a sense of well-being. <em>Delayed</em> expectations may result in curiosity, suspense or anxiety. <em>Thwarted</em> expectations may result in somewhat unpleasant emotions like disappointment or frustration. 
		</p>

		<div id="graphic_5_out" class="lectureQuestion">
