<div id="section_3">
	<div class="section">
		<h3>CONVENTION IN ACTION</h3>
		<p>
			Let's think about some examples of this relationship between convention and expectation and how filmmakers might choose to make use of them.
		</p>
		<p>
			Genre filmmaking is often a breeding ground for convention (in fact, you could make an argument that a genre is nothing but a collection of conventions). Here's a convention from horror films: 	
		</p>	
		<p>
			Character X is alone in the house. Character X hears something in a different part of the house and goes to investigate. Most likely there's some spooky music playing. 
		</p>
		<p>
			What are your expectations regarding what's going to happen? You've seen this so many times that it's become pretty obvious. Character X encounters the villain and gets killed in some gruesome fashion. At least that's how the convention started. Hearing the sound and going to investigate is a way to create suspense, followed by a shock when the moment of truth arrives. The viewer knows what's going to happen. The only question is when that expectation will be fulfilled.
		</p>
		<p>
			Conventions, however, are fluid. They don't remain static. They evolve over time. At some point the above convention got tiresome (you could probably make a case that it was always tiresome). After some repetition, it becomes entirely predictable. Once the viewer knows the filmmaker's strategy, then the filmmaker has to change strategies to try to get a step ahead of the viewer's expectations. Here's a scene from <em>Alien</em> by Ridley Scott that presents a variation on the original convention:	
		</p>	
		<p>
			The heroes hear something and go to find it. The heroes (and the viewer) are led to believe that they've found it. The filmmaker has established the expectation that we're about to encounter the alien. However, this time, the filmmaker chooses to thwart that expectation rather than fulfill it, resulting in a slightly more complex range of emotions. At the height of suspense, the danger is revealed to be something harmless, and both the viewer and characters let their guard down, experiencing a sense of relief and perhaps even some degree of humor (note the complexity of moving from fear and suspense to shock to relief and laughter).
		</p>
		<p>
			However, you've seen this variation many times before as well, so much so that we can say that this variation has also become it's own convention. Does anyone (who hasn't seen <em>Alien</em>), want to venture a guess as to what happens next? (Hint: to the guy who goes after the cat?). 
		</p>
		<p>
			The filmmaker builds up the suspense, then punctures it by revealing that there was no danger. Then when we no longer expect danger, it strikes suddenly (Yes, I'm afraid Harry Dean Stanton is doomed), and Ridley Scott is able to have his cake and eat it too, putting the viewer through suspenseful agony, but still able to pop a surprise on the viewer as well. This is a rather different emotional experience from the first version where the character hears something and then gets killed. 
		</p>
		<p>
			But as the viewer becomes accustomed to this convention as well, a war of escalation takes place, with the filmmaker having to constantly try to get one step ahead of the viewer, and you can end up with a film experience that functions something like an elaborate game. The viewer says, "I know what you're doing." The filmmaker responds "I know that you know what I'm doing."
			"I know that you know that I know what your'e doing."
			"I know that you know that I know that you know what I'm doing." etc.
		</p>
		<p>
			This scene from <em>A Perfect Getaway</em> illustrates this idea of a filmmaker playing games with the viewer:	
		</p>
		<p>
			There's a bit of a taunt contained in this scene. The filmmaker is saying, Hey, I know that you know that this is a genre movie and that you have a certain set of expectations. By acknowledging the game, the filmmaker throws the viewer off track. Now when the filmmaker actively employs a cliche, we don't know whether to take it at face value or to expect some sort of misdirection (hint for this movie: expect misdirection). 
		</p>
		<p>
			In essence, this can be one description of the entirety of the process of making a narrative film. The filmmaker is engaging with the entire history of filmmaking, working off expectations created by others, playing with and against ideas used many times by other filmmakers.	
		</p>
		<p>
			A significant part of the moviemaking process has become the task of manipulating and controlling viewer expectation. This is why an understanding of all the variables within the narrative system is so important: because viewer expectations depend entirely on the history of this system. 
		</p>
	</div>
